text: After completing this project we had the great oppertunity to do a presentation infront of the entire AKQA San Francisco office.  Jeffery Qua and myself stood in an room of 450 sets of eyes and ears that watched and listened to what we had made.
title: Presentation

text:
Our design prompt was but a utterance over lunch about replacing a leaving employee with a robot.  We were unsure of what we were out to solve. Regardless, we put on our designers hats and went to best resource we knew at the time IDEOs Method Cards. We better shaped our problem by journey mapping the process between AKQA and Nike 2014s March Madness Campaign. Our journey map reveal that the process had many pain points: 

- Launches were often tied to an event and therefore deadlines were non-negotiable.
- Creative handoffs often bleed into execution timelines.
- Expensive production cost in both design and technology departements.
- Physical distance between AKQA and Nike caused long feedback turn arounds.
- AKQA Designers used Photoshop which didnt offer a good solution for Responsive design.
- Nikes CMS CQ5 was slow and required a certified trained Authorer to use it.

 These pain points were used to help framed the product requirements.
title: Identifing Pain Points.

values.description: I have personally known Marcus for over 10 years. And since the first year, I've known him to be an artist. Marcus has a way of picking up any creative task and making it original. His creative process is a personal one; more importantly, it is a process that I've watch him iterate and evolve based on feedback. Marcus is a careful listener.  Most recently, I have subcontracted Marcus for a client work (Earthseed), where he was able to carefully take in the client and stakeholder's product requirements and deliver successful work. It has always been a joy to work with Marcus Thompson and I'm looking forward to the day I can work with him again.
values.name: Marcus Thompson
values.title: Graphic Designer

Ruby lifts team members, owns projects, and has a laser sharp focus on the details.
I've worked with Ruby for nearly 2 years on Uber.com.
Uber.com collaborated with over 10 lines of business(LoB) and each LoB had many stakeholders and each stakeholder had 10 new ideas daily (bit hyperbole). Luckily, with Ruby, I never had to filter the signal from the noise and when Ruby gave me tasks and projects, I could always trusted that they were properly vetted.
